                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "road",
                    "text" : [ { "text" : "### Roads\n\nFigure 1 depicts a section of the archaeological site of Teotihuacan in Mexico",
                                 "source" : null,
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                               "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"ChronologyTeotihuacan\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('ChronologyTeotihuacan', '0%')\" src=\"images/TeotihuacanGeneral.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/>Figure 1: General view of Teotihuacan. Photograph taken on <span class=\"htdate\"></span>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
                               { "text" : "The indigenous peoples of the Americas (*Abya Yala*) not only built roads within their cities but also developed extensive networks connecting different regions. For example, the Mayas constructed **sacbes** (plural: **sacbeob**), which were white roads designed to simplify movement between cities",
                                 "source" : [
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "19ea1063-0ddd-4468-ad3e-2635675ca68d",
                                                "text": "LaRocque, A., Leblon, B., Ek, J., and Folan, W. J.",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2022", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                               { "text" : "In the southern part of the continent, the Incas created an impressive network of routes spanning 39,000 kilometers, known as the **Qhapaq Ñan**, which linked diverse regions. Portions of these routes were originally built by earlier civilizations, such as the Wari",
                                 "source" : [
                                              { "type": 1,
                                                "uuid": "0bc6455e-7fdb-49cd-bf29-c3675aca4d4f",
                                                "text": "Jurado, L. R. C. V., pp. 1270 - 1271",
                                                "date" :  {"type" : "gregory", "year" : "2018", "month" : "-1", "day" : "-1" }}
                                 ],
                                 "isTable" : false,
                                 "fill_dates" : null,
                                 "format" : "markdown",
                                 "PostMention": ":"
                               },
                               "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: On Roads</b><br /><br />Roads are not exclusive to the indigenous peoples of the Americas (<i>Abya Yala</i>). Even today, we continue to build streets, highways, and routes that serve similar purposes—facilitating movement and connection between cities.<br /><br />Additionally, rivers, which follow natural courses, have been and continue to be used as pathways by various cultures around the world.<br /><br />Can you identify any connections between texts and roads?</div></div></center></p>"
